<BaseLayout
  title="Dryer Not Heating? Here's What's Wrong and How to Fix It | DMV Appliance Repair"
  description="A dryer that runs but produces no heat almost always has a blown thermal fuse or failed heating element. Here's how to diagnose and fix a dryer with no heat."
  schemaType="article"
  schemaMeta={{
    headline: "Dryer Not Heating? Here's What's Wrong and How to Fix It",
    description: "A dryer that runs but produces no heat almost always has a blown thermal fuse or failed heating element. Here's how to diagnose and fix a dryer with no heat.",
    datePublished: "2025-01-15T00:00:00Z",
    url: "https://dmvappliance.com/resources/dryer-not-heating/",
  }}
>
  <article class="resource-article">
    <header class="article-header section--slate">
      <div class="container article-header-inner">
        <a href="/resources/" class="article-back-link">← Back to Resources</a>
        <a href="/services/dryer-repair/" class="article-service-tag">Dryer Repair</a>
        <h1>Dryer Not Heating? Here's What's Wrong and How to Fix It</h1>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>By DMV Appliance Repair</span>
          <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
          <span>6 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="article-body section">
      <div class="container article-body-inner">
        <div class="article-content">

          <p class="article-lead">
            A dryer that runs its full cycle but leaves clothes damp — or one that you can tell isn't producing any heat at all — almost always comes down to one of a handful of parts. Most of these are straightforward repairs.
          </p>

          <h2>The most likely causes</h2>

          <h3>1. Blown thermal fuse (most common)</h3>
          <p>
            The thermal fuse is a safety device designed to blow if the dryer overheats. When it goes, the dryer typically continues to run — tumbling, timing, cycling through settings — but produces zero heat. Most homeowners don't realize their thermal fuse has blown because the dryer seems to "work" until they notice the clothes are still wet.
          </p>
          <p>
            The thermal fuse is a one-time use component. Once it blows, it has to be replaced. But here's the important part: if it blew, something made the dryer overheat. The most common cause is a clogged or kinked exhaust duct. If you replace the thermal fuse without addressing the underlying cause, it will blow again.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Check your exhaust duct first.</strong> Pull the dryer away from the wall and inspect the ductwork. If it's collapsed, kinked, or blocked, clear it before anything else. A full duct cleaning — from the dryer to the exterior vent — should be part of the repair.
          </p>

          <h3>2. Failed heating element (electric dryers)</h3>
          <p>
            Electric dryers heat air by passing it over a coil of resistance wire — the heating element. When a section of that coil breaks, it can short out the entire heating circuit. Unlike a thermal fuse, a failed heating element doesn't always look burned from the outside, so you'll usually need a multimeter to test continuity.
          </p>
          <p>
            Heating elements are model-specific parts, but they're widely available for most brands (Whirlpool, GE, LG, Samsung, Maytag, Frigidaire). Replacement requires disassembly of the dryer cabinet — front panel and drum removal on most models. Not a hard job for someone comfortable with appliances, but it takes 1-2 hours.
          </p>

          <h3>3. Igniter failure (gas dryers)</h3>
          <p>
            On gas dryers, heat comes from a burner ignited by a glow-bar igniter. The igniter glows red-hot to ignite the gas, then cools. Over time, igniters develop hairline cracks and eventually fail to reach ignition temperature.
          </p>
          <p>
            A common sign: the dryer starts, you can see the igniter glowing, but it never lights and the burner never kicks on. That's classic igniter failure. The gas valve coils can cause the same symptom, so both should be tested.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Safety note:</strong> If you smell gas when troubleshooting, stop immediately and call your gas company. A failed igniter itself doesn't cause a gas leak, but don't rule out other issues.
          </p>

          <h3>4. Cycling thermostat or high-limit thermostat failure</h3>
          <p>
            Dryers have multiple thermostats that regulate heat during the cycle. The cycling thermostat turns heat on and off to maintain the target temperature. The high-limit thermostat cuts heat if the dryer gets dangerously hot. When either fails in the open position, the dryer gets no heat. When they fail in the closed position, the dryer can overheat — which then blows the thermal fuse.
          </p>

          <h3>5. Timer or control board failure</h3>
          <p>
            Less common, but if the timer motor or control board isn't advancing through cycles correctly, heat signals may not be sent. This is worth checking if you've replaced the thermal fuse and heating element and the dryer still has issues.
          </p>

          <h2>What you can try yourself</h2>

          <ol class="article-steps">
            <li>
              <strong>Clean the lint trap and exhaust duct.</strong> This is free and should be your first step regardless. Pull the dryer out from the wall. Disconnect and inspect the flexible duct section — if it's made of white plastic accordion duct, consider replacing it with rigid metal duct. Clean out any lint blockage from the duct run to the exterior vent.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Reset the circuit breaker.</strong> Electric dryers run on a double-pole 240V circuit breaker. If one leg has tripped, the dryer will run (motor is 120V) but won't heat (element needs 240V). Go to your breaker panel and check whether the dryer breaker has tripped. Reset it fully before concluding it's a component failure.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Check the start button / control settings.</strong> Some dryers have an "air only" or "fluff" cycle that runs without heat. Make sure you're not accidentally running it on a no-heat setting.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Locate and test the thermal fuse.</strong> The thermal fuse is typically mounted on the exhaust duct inside the dryer, near the burner or heating element. It's a small, oval plastic component with two wires. Disconnect power, remove the back panel or front panel (model dependent), locate the fuse, and test it with a multimeter set to continuity. No continuity = blown fuse.
            </li>
          </ol>

          <h2>When to call for a repair</h2>
          <p>
            If you've cleared the exhaust duct, reset the breaker, and confirmed the thermal fuse is blown — you're looking at a repair that involves getting into the dryer cabinet to replace parts. At that point, it makes sense to have a technician come out because:
          </p>
          <ul class="article-bullets">
            <li>A blown thermal fuse means you need to identify and fix the underlying cause, not just replace the fuse</li>
            <li>If the heating element has also failed, you'll want to replace both in one visit</li>
            <li>Gas dryer repairs near the burner assembly should be done by someone with experience</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="article-cta-box">
            <h3>Need a dryer repair in the DMV?</h3>
            <p>
              We carry thermal fuses and heating elements for most major dryer brands on the truck.
              Most dryer no-heat repairs are completed in a single visit. Call or request a callback below.
            </p>
            <div class="article-cta-actions">
              <a href="tel:+17038667776" class="btn btn--primary">703-866-7776 (VA)</a>
              <a href="tel:+13019076666" class="btn btn--outline">301-907-6666 (MD)</a>
              <a href="#booking" class="btn btn--outline">Request Callback</a>
            </div>
            <p class="article-cta-note">
              $60 off every completed repair · Free service call when we do the work · Warranty on parts and labor
            </p>
          </div>

          <h2>Dryer maintenance tips to prevent this</h2>
          <ul class="article-bullets">
            <li>Clean the lint trap before every load — not after, before. It takes 3 seconds.</li>
            <li>Have the exhaust duct professionally cleaned once a year. A clogged duct is the single most common cause of dryer failure and house fires.</li>
            <li>Replace plastic accordion duct with rigid or semi-rigid metal duct. Plastic accordion duct accumulates lint more easily and can kink.</li>
            <li>Don't run the dryer while you sleep or when you're not home. A dryer fire can start quickly, especially with a restricted exhaust.</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="article-see-also">
            See also: <a href="/services/dryer-repair/">Dryer Repair in the DMV</a>
          </p>

        </div>

        <aside class="article-sidebar">
          <div class="sidebar-box">
            <h3 class="sidebar-heading">Need a repair?</h3>
            <p>We carry parts for most major dryer brands. Same-day service 7 days a week.</p>
            <div class="sidebar-phones">
